<DIV1 TYPE="declaration">
<PB N="109" REF="58">
<HEAD><HI>In the I&s;land</HI> BARBADAS, May <HI>the third,</HI> An. Dom. 1650.</HEAD>
<P><HI>CHARLES STVART,</HI> Son to the late King, was with great &s;olemnity proclaimed King of <HI>England, Scotland, France</HI> and <HI>Ireland &amp;c.</HI> Immediately thereupon the Booke of Com|mon Prayer was declared, to be the only Pattern of true wor&s;hip, And com|manded to be di&s;tinctly, and duly read in every Pari&s;h Church, every Lords Day &amp;c.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>H. GOVLDVVELL. Secretary.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="order">
<PB N="110" REF="59">
<HEAD><HI>At a Meeting of the</HI> Gover|nour, Coun&s;ell <HI>and</HI> A&s;&s;embly, <HI>May</HI> the 7.</HEAD>
<P>THE RIGHT HONORABLE, <HI>Francis</HI> Lord <HI>Willougby</HI> of <HI>Parham,</HI> having brought a Commi&s;sion from the Right Honorable, <HI>James</HI> Earle of <HI>Carlile,</HI> as his Lieutenant Generall of all the Crebe I&s;lands, his Honour was willingly, and humbly received, and his Commi&s;sion ac|cepted of according to the Power and Con|tents thereof; And whereas it was the humble de&s;ires of the <HI>Governour, Coun&s;ell,</HI> and <HI>A&s;&s;embly,</HI> to the Right Honorable the Lieutenant Generall, That in re&s;pect of the incertainty and distractions of the pre|&s;ent Times, his Lord&s;hip would plea&s;e to con|de&s;cend to the continuance of this pre&s;ent A&s;&s;embly, and Government, under all Offices both Civill, and Mar&s;hall, for the &s;pace of three moneths. His Lord&s;hip was plea|&s;ed to a&s;&s;ent thereunto; and ordered accord|ingly.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED><HI>H. Goldwell,</HI> Sec.</SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="postscript">
<PB N="111" REF="59">
<HEAD>POST-SCRIPT.</HEAD>
<P>WHereas the Reader may haply be &s;o curious, as to de&s;ire the Names of tho&s;e per&s;ons that have &s;uffered in the I&s;land <HI>Barbadas;</HI> He may take notice that <HI>John Web&s;ter,</HI> Mate to Captaine <HI>Benjamin Treneman,</HI> had his Tongue cut, and was burned in both Cheekes with the Letter <HI>T.</HI> Al&s;o Lieutenant <HI>John Brandon</HI> was burn'd in the Cheekes as afore&s;aid: the&s;e both &s;uffered the 12 day of <HI>January,</HI> 1649. about twelve a Clock; And whereas you finde the Di&s;coverer of our Enemies mi&s;|chievous intentions to be deciphered only by <HI>L. C. C. C.</HI> the Gentleman is Lieutenant Colonell <HI>Chri&s;topher Coddrington.</HI> Like|wi&s;e the Colonells Name that rai&s;ed the Regiment, which you finde &s;pake of that was betrayd, is Colonell <HI>Thomas Modi|ford;</HI>
<PB N="112" REF="60"> one thing you may take notice of, That &s;ince the committing of this to the Pre&s;&s;e, there are divers more of our Bani&s;hed Brethren come for <HI>England;</HI> and where|as you finde the Enemies of our Peace, in their Propo&s;itions, promi&s;ing to main|taine and defend Captaine <HI>Phillip Bell,</HI> to continue Governour of that I&s;land, they have turned him out with as much di&s;grace, as they promi&s;ed Fidelity. &dtridot;</P>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
